# Creating a NEW GitHub repo: the capability that taught us the most.
#
# It has been "fixed" FOUR times and refuted four times. Each refutation was a
# real experiment. Do not propose a fifth fix without reading all four.
#
# THE WALL, precisely: POST /user/repos accepts only an OAuth-App token or a PAT
# (classic, or fine-grained with Administration write). It does NOT accept a
# GitHub App token, whether an installation token OR a user-to-server token.
# GitHub's tell is: 403 "Resource not accessible by integration".
#
# What was tried, and what happened:
#
#   1. The built-in GitHub tools (Claude GitHub App installation token)
#      -> 403. Expected: App tokens cannot create user-owned repos.
#
#   2. A user PAT placed in GH_TOKEN in the cloud environment
#      -> 403, and NOT from GitHub. The session's agent proxy enforces an
#      authorized repository set and refuses to inject or forward a credential
#      for paths outside it. The call never reached GitHub. (claude-code#76248)
#
#   3. GitHub's official remote MCP server added as a CUSTOM connector,
#      OAuth'd through Anthropic (verified: get_me -> barmoshe)
#      -> The connector LOADS in a cloud session, bypasses the proxy entirely,
#      and authenticates as the real user. GitHub still returned
#      403 "Resource not accessible by integration". Why: Anthropic's
#      "Claude Github MCP Connector" is itself a GITHUB APP (client id Iv23li...),
#      so its OAuth yields a user-to-server token, still bound by the App's
#      permissions rather than by the scopes shown at consent. It changed the
#      identity, not the token shape.
#
#   4. Same connector, but with a user-registered classic OAUTH APP supplied via
#      the connector's Advanced settings (client id/secret; the oauth_anthropic_creds
#      "bring your own OAuth app" flow). An OAuth-App token (Ov23li..., gho_) WOULD
#      be accepted by POST /user/repos, so this should have worked.
#      -> It did not. claude.ai SILENTLY IGNORED the supplied client id and
#      re-authorized through Anthropic's own GitHub App instead. Confirmed at
#      github.com/settings/applications: the user's OAuth App never appears under
#      Authorized OAuth Apps, while "Claude Github MCP Connector" is present under
#      Authorized GitHub Apps. For GitHub's hosted MCP server, the BYO-OAuth
#      override does not take effect; it pins its own client.
#
# So the connector channel is genuinely open (a real, useful finding) but there is
# no way to make it present a PAT- or OAuth-App-shaped token, which is the one
# thing this endpoint requires.
#
# What actually works: a local session (gh / a PAT, no proxy, no App). Or an
# executor that runs somewhere without the proxy and holds a real PAT, e.g. a
# GitHub Actions workflow with the PAT in Actions secrets.

Capability github.repo-create
  Description Create a NEW GitHub repository (requires an OAuth-App token or a PAT; a GitHub App token can never do it)
  Probe env GH_TOKEN
  Probe env GITHUB_TOKEN
  Probe file ~/.config/gh/hosts.yml
  Unless env CLAUDE_CODE_REMOTE
  Blocked Cloud session: not achievable from here by any known configuration. The agent proxy blocks a PAT used in-VM, and every GitHub MCP route (built-in AND a user-OAuth custom connector) authenticates as a GitHub App, whose token GitHub refuses for POST /user/repos with 403 "Resource not accessible by integration". Verified 2026-07-14. Create the repo from a local session, or delegate to a GitHub Actions workflow holding a real PAT.
  Requires An OAuth-App token or a PAT (classic with repo scope, or fine-grained with Administration write). A GitHub App token is NEVER sufficient, installation or user-to-server. AND an egress path not filtered to an authorized repo set.
  Remediation From a LOCAL session this already works (gh is authenticated). From cloud there is no configuration fix: delegate instead. Push to the session's bound repo and let a GitHub Actions workflow create the target repo using a PAT stored in Actions secrets; the workflow runs on GitHub infrastructure, where no proxy applies and the token is a real PAT. Do NOT put a PAT in the cloud environment (the proxy blocks it, and there is no secrets store). Do NOT expect a GitHub MCP connector to fix it (tested: it loads and authenticates as you, and GitHub still refuses).
  Risk high
  Environments local

Capability github.repo-write
  Description Read and write repos that are in THIS session's authorized set (issues, PRs, comments, pushes)
  Probe http https://api.github.com
  Requires The Claude GitHub App connection or a synced gh token, AND the target repo must be one of this session's configured sources.
  Remediation Works for the repos this session was opened against. For a repo OUTSIDE that set, the proxy refuses the write and will not inject a credential, whatever token you hold: open a session whose sources include that repo, or act on it from a local session. Acting on the repo you are bound to is fine; reaching a different one is not.
  Risk low
  Environments local cloud ci

# The connector channel IS open, and that is worth knowing for capabilities that
# do NOT need a PAT-shaped token. Custom claude.ai connectors load in cloud
# sessions and their traffic bypasses the VM network allowlist entirely, which is
# how Vercel deploys work from a locked-down VM.
Capability mcp.custom-connectors
  Description Custom claude.ai MCP connectors load in this session (their traffic bypasses the VM network allowlist)
  Probe env CLAUDE_CODE_REMOTE
  Requires A connector added on claude.ai and enabled for the session
  Remediation Verified 2026-07-14: a custom connector loaded in a cloud session alongside the first-party GitHub one and its tools were callable. If a capability is blocked by the VM's network allowlist, an MCP connector is the way around it. It cannot, however, change what CREDENTIAL TYPE the far end authenticates with, so it does not unlock GitHub repo creation. Route reachability problems through connectors; route permission problems through delegation.
  Risk low
  Environments cloud
